 safari logistics — park fees, ranger tips, guide contacts, and crater-day details — sourced from the official tariff PDF and a voice-memo transcription. I never fabricate fee amounts, contact names, or policy details; every answer cites an actual knowledge file or a research finding.\n/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/harness/.state/local-server/pod-root/.lmthing/tanzania-trip/spaces/ngorongoro-advisor/knowledge/safari/ngorongoro/guide-contacts.md:3:Two distinct contacts are involved in the Ngorongoro safari: Richard is the main office contact — he handles safari arrangements and receives the balance payment. Do not confuse him with Emmanuel, who is the driver guide for the crater day. Emmanuel was described as very knowledgeable, excellent at spotting wildlife, and pointed things out before they were even visible.\n/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/harness/.state/local-server/pod-root/.lmthing/tanzania-trip/spaces/ngorongoro-advisor/knowledge/safari/ngorongoro/index.md:10:**Ranger Tips:** A potential extra ranger tip (~TZS 5,000 cash at the gate) was mentioned by the driver guide but not communicated in advance — this needs clarification with the office contact before final payment.\n/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/harness/.state/local-server/pod-root/.lmthing/tanzania-trip/spaces/ngorongoro-advisor/knowledge/safari/ngorongoro/index.md:12:**Guide Contacts:** Richard is the main office contact for safari arrangements and balance payment; Emmanuel is the driver guide (distinct from Richard), very knowledgeable and skilled at spotting wildlife.\n/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/harness/.state/local-server/pod-root/.lmthing/tanzania-trip/spaces/ngorongoro-advisor/knowledge/safari/ngorongoro/index.md:14:**Crater Day Details:** The experience included close-up wildlife everywhere (Emmanuel pointed things out before they were visible), and a Maasai lady selling beaded bracelets at the rim — two purchased for ~TZS 35,000 (~$20–25 USD).\n/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/harness/.state/local-server/pod-root/.lmthing/tanzania-trip/spaces/stone-town-zanzibar/knowledge/stone-town/architecture/swahili-coastal-design.md:3:Swahili coastal architecture, of which Stone Town is the preeminent surviving example, is defined by its inward-facing orientation and fusion of influences from across the Indian Ocean world. Buildings typically present plain, whitewashed coral-stone walls to the narrow alleyways, concealing cool interior courtyards, ornate reception halls (baraza), and private family quarters. This design responds both to the hot, humid climate — courtyards draw cool air upward — and to Islamic cultural values of privacy and modesty. The architectural vocabulary blends Omani Arab arcades, Persian stucco ornament, Indian carved timberwork, and African spatial organization. Stone Town's UNESCO World Heritage designation recognizes this unique synthesis as an outstanding material record of centuries of monsoon-driven trade and cultural exchange along the Swahili Coast.\n/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/harness/.state/local-server/pod-root/.lmthing/tanzania-trip/spaces/tanzania-trip-overview/knowledge/tanzania-trip-2026/notes/index.md:6:Trip notes for the Tanzania & Egypt journey, Aug 3–20, 2026, with Vasileios Kefallinos and Athina Mari. Covers the **itinerary** day-by-day across Ngorongoro Crater, Stone Town/Zanzibar, and Egypt as documented in tanzaniamemories.md. Lists **contacts**: Richard (safari office — handles arrangements and balance payment) and Emmanuel (driver guide for the Ngorongoro crater day, not the same person as Richard). Surfaces **logistics** including the ranger tip at Ngorongoro (~TZS 5,000) that needs clarification with Richard, and the bracelet purchase (~TZS 35,000) whose exact amount is uncertain.\n/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/harness/.state/local-server/pod-root/.lmthing/tanzania-trip/spaces/stone-town-zanzibar/knowledge/zanzibar/trip-context/tanzania-aug-2026.md:3:The Tanzania trip took place in August 2026 and included Zanzibar as a distinct leg with its own character — coastal atmosphere, historic Stone Town, and the iconic architecture of the Swahili coast. Stone Town is the historic heart of Zanzibar City, a UNESCO World Heritage site known for its labyrinthine alleys and fusion of Arab, Persian, Indian, and European architectural influences. The trip notes document this as part of a broader Tanzanian itinerary.\n/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/harness/.state/local-server/pod-root/.lmthing/tanzania-trip/spaces/stone-town-zanzibar/knowledge/zanzibar/trip-context/index.md:6:Context for the Zanzibar leg of the Tanzania trip (Aug 2026). Stone Town, the historic heart of Zanzibar City and a UNESCO World Heritage site, is characterised by labyrinthine alleys, carved wooden doors, and a fusion of Arab, Persian, Indian, and European influences. The \"tanzania-aug-2026\" aspect covers the broader trip framing, while \"photo-details\" covers the specific courtyard photograph taken in Stone Town — a tall, narrow light well with white stucco walls, ornate wooden balconies, and dramatic filtered light, typical of inward-facing Swahili coastal design.\n/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/harness/.state/local-server/pod-root/.lmthing/tanzania-trip/spaces/stone-town-zanzibar/knowledge/stone-town/architecture/index.md:6:Stone Town, the historic heart of Zanzibar City and a UNESCO World Heritage site, is renowned for its fusion of Arab, Persian, Indian, and European architectural influences. Its architecture is defined by three key elements: hidden interior courtyards — tall, narrow light wells with white stucco walls and ornate wooden balconies that create dramatic, inward-facing spaces; intricately carved wooden doors — a signature feature of Zanzibari buildings, often adorned with brass studs and symbolic motifs; and the broader Swahili coastal design tradition — an inward-facing layout of labyrinthine alleys and private interior spaces that reflects centuries of monsoon-driven trade and cultural exchange along the East African coast.\n/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/harness/.state/local-server/pod-root/.lmthing/tanzania-trip/spaces/tanzania-trip-overview/knowledge/tanzania-trip-2026/notes/contacts.md:5:- **Richard** — main safari office contact. Handles all safari arrangements and the balance payment. He is the go-to person for financial and logistical questions, including the outstanding ranger tip clarification.\n/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/harness/.state/local-server/pod-root/.lmthing/tanzania-trip/spaces/tanzania-trip-overview/knowledge/tanzania-trip-2026/notes/contacts.md:6:- **Emmanuel** — driver guide specifically for the Ngorongoro crater day. Described as very knowledgeable. He is not the same person as Richard; he handles on-the-ground guiding during the crater visit.\n/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/harness/.state/local-server/pod-root/.lmthing/tanzania-trip/spaces/tanzania-trip-overview/knowledge/tanzania-trip-2026/traveler-info/index.md:6:Traveler information for the Tanzania & Egypt trip, Aug 3–20, 2026. Covers the two travelers (Vasileios Kefallinos and Athina Mari) and their multi-country itinerary across Tanzania and Egypt. Also tracks open items that need resolution before or during the trip, including the Ngorongoro ranger tip (~TZS 5,000) to be clarified with Richard, and the uncertain bracelet purchase amount (~TZS 35,000).\n/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/harness/.state/local-server/pod-root/.lmthing/tanzania-trip/spaces/ngorongoro-advisor/knowledge/safari/ngorongoro/crater-day-details.md:3:The Ngorongoro Crater day was described as one of the best days of the trip — wildlife everywhere, right up close, with Emmanuel pointing things out before they were visible. On the way out at the rim, a Maasai lady was selling beaded bracelets. Two bracelets were purchased for Athina Mari. The price was approximately $20–25 USD total, paid around TZS 35,000 in shillings — the exact amount is uncertain as it wasn't written down immediately.\n/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/harness/.state/local-server/pod-root/.lmthing/tanzania-trip/spaces/stone-town-zanzibar/knowledge/stone-town/architecture/stone-town-zanzibar.md:1:> source: researched\n/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/harness/.state/local-server/pod-root/.lmthing/tanzania-trip/spaces/stone-town-zanzibar/knowledge/stone-town/architecture/stone-town-zanzibar.md:3:Stone Town, Zanzibar — a UNESCO World Heritage Site since 2000 (recognized for its outstanding Swahili coastal trading-town architecture) — is famed for its over 560 hand-carved wooden doors, the oldest dating to 1694 AD. These doors blend African, Arab, Indian, and European influences, with designs encoding the owner's heritage: geometric patterns (Arab/Indian) versus lotus and chain motifs (Swahili). The architecture features coral-stone buildings, narrow winding streets, hidden courtyards, and ornate balconies. Key landmarks include the House of Wonders, Old Fort, Sultan's Palace, and the Anglican Cathedral on the former slave-market site.\n/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/harness/.state/local-server/pod-root/.lmthing/tanzania-trip/spaces/ngorongoro-advisor/tasklists/research_and_store/02-store.md:17:const w = writeKnowledge('safari','ngorongoro', slug, String(research.answer), { source: 'researched' });\n/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/harness/.state/local-server/pod-root/.lmthing/tanzania-trip/spaces/tanzania-trip-overview/knowledge/tanzania-trip-2026/costs/index.md:6:Cost breakdown for the Tanzania & Egypt trip (Aug 3–20, 2026), drawn from the trip-costs.xlsx spreadsheet. Covers safari costs, park fees, tips (including an uncertain ~TZS 5,000 ranger tip at Ngorongoro), and a bracelet purchase (~TZS 35,000) whose exact amount is still uncertain. All figures should be cross-checked with Richard before the safari balance payment is finalized.\n/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/harness/.state/local-server/pod-root/.lmthing/tanzania-trip/spaces/ngorongoro-advisor/knowledge/safari/ngorongoro/ranger-tips.md:1:# ranger-tips\n/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/harness/.state/local-server/pod-root/.lmthing/tanzania-trip/spaces/ngorongoro-advisor/knowledge/safari/ngorongoro/ranger-tips.md:3:The driver guide Emmanuel mentioned that there is sometimes an extra ranger tip expected at the Ngorongoro gate — approximately TZS 5,000, paid in cash, separate from the official park fees. This was not communicated beforehand by the office contact Richard. Action item: ask Richard about this before making the safari balance payment to avoid surprises on crater day.\n/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/harness/.state/local-server/pod-root/.lmthing/tanzania-trip/spaces/tanzania-trip-overview/knowledge/tanzania-trip-2026/notes/itinerary.md:5:1. **Ngorongoro Crater** — safari day with driver guide Emmanuel, exploring the crater floor.\n/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/harness/.state/local-server/pod-root/.lmthing/tanzania-trip/spaces/stone-town-zanzibar/tasklists/research_and_store/02-store.md:17:const w = writeKnowledge('stone-town','architecture', slug, String(research.answer), { source: 'researched' });","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
